    <div class="post-body" itemprop="articleBody">

      
      

      
        <h2 id="Introduction"><a href="#Introduction" class="headerlink" title="Introduction"></a>Introduction</h2><p>This is the second post of Hadoop series. In this post, we will install hadoop High Availability (HA) on the multi-node cluster we created in the first post. If you have a cluster from <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Amazon AWS</a>, <a href="https://cloud.google.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google GCP</a>, or <a href="https://azure.microsoft.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Microsoft Azure</a>, the procedure will be similar. Commertially, you may choose a ready-to-use Hadoop distribution from <a href="https://www.hortonworks.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Hortonworks</a>, <a href="https://www.cloudera.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Cloudera</a>, or <a href="https://mapr.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MapR</a>, but it’s still beneficial to have some basic ideas of how the Hadoop barebone works.</p>
<p>This is a slightly long post, but if you follow along, you’ll find it’s really not that difficult to have a cluster running on your computer, so you can play with the basic concepts like map-reduce or later on Apache Spark whenever you want to.</p>
<a id="more"></a>
<p>The following is the output we are targeting. We’ll have two namenodes (one in charge, the other standing by) and three datanodes.</p>
<p><strong>VM System:</strong> <a href="https://www.ubuntu.com/download/server" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ubuntu 16.04 server</a></p>
<p><strong>zookeeper:</strong> vm01, vm02, vm03, vm04, vm05</p>
<p><strong>Namenode:</strong> vm01, vm02</p>
<p><strong>Datanode:</strong> vm03, vm04, vm05</p>
<p><strong>Resource Manager:</strong> vm01, vm02</p>
<p><strong>Journal Node:</strong> vm01, vm02, vm03, vm04, vm05</p>
<h2 id="Install-XShell"><a href="#Install-XShell" class="headerlink" title="Install XShell"></a>Install XShell</h2><p>At beginning, let’s install some useful tools. <a href="https://www.netsarang.com/products/xsh_overview.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Xshell</a> is a software used for remote login. Another popular choice is <a href="http://www.putty.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PuTTY</a>. You are able to log on to the five machines at the same time, as shown below.</p>
<img src="/cloud-service-two/xshell.png" title="xshell to virtual machines">
<h2 id="Install-WinSCP-Optional"><a href="#Install-WinSCP-Optional" class="headerlink" title="Install WinSCP (Optional)"></a>Install WinSCP (Optional)</h2><p><a href="https://winscp.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WinSCP</a> is used to upload unzipped files to cloud servers. Usually I download hadoop and unzip it in Windows, then upload the unzipped onto server machine. This process is equivalent to the following command</p>
<figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">wget url</span><br><span class="line">tar -xvzf file</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<h2 id="Name-the-Machines"><a href="#Name-the-Machines" class="headerlink" title="Name the Machines"></a>Name the Machines</h2><p>Take vm01 as example, in order to refer to it by name vm01 instead of by IP address, we need to give it a name.</p>
<p>First find its ip address via command <font color="blue">ifconfig</font>, on my machine its <font color="blue">192.168.1.198</font>. Then type in vm01 in /etc/hostname,</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">sudo vim /etc/hostname</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<p><strong>Do this for vm02~vm05</strong>. and note their ip address, usually they are consecutive.</p>
<p>Next, go back to vm01, add all five virtual machines in /etc/hosts</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">sudo vim /etc/hosts</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">192.168.1.198    vm01</span><br><span class="line">192.168.1.199    vm02</span><br><span class="line">192.168.1.200    vm03</span><br><span class="line">192.168.1.201    vm04</span><br><span class="line">192.168.1.202    vm05</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<p>Again, <strong>do this for vm02~vm05</strong>. After that, you should be able to ping machines by name, for example,</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">ping vm02</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<h2 id="Create-user-hadoop-Optional"><a href="#Create-user-hadoop-Optional" class="headerlink" title="Create user hadoop (Optional)"></a>Create user hadoop (Optional)</h2><p>As part of the standard practice for Hadoop, we create a user called hadoop and add it to sudo group.<br><figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">sudo adduser hadoop</span><br><span class="line">sudo usermod -aG sudo hadoop</span><br><span class="line">sudo su hadoop</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<p>From now on, we’ll log in as user hadoop and operate in its home folder ~ or /home/hadoop. In particular, all softwares will be installed in /home/hadoop/softwares, data and logs will be directed into /home/hadoop/runtime.</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="built_in">cd</span> ~</span><br><span class="line">mkdir softwares runtime</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<h2 id="Setp-up-SSH"><a href="#Setp-up-SSH" class="headerlink" title="Setp up SSH"></a>Setp up SSH</h2><p>It allows hadoop to log into vm01~vm05 without password. Execute the following on vm01.</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">su hadoop		<span class="comment"># user hadoop</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="built_in">cd</span> ~			<span class="comment"># hadoop home dir</span></span><br><span class="line">mkdir .ssh		<span class="comment"># create folder</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="built_in">cd</span> .ssh			<span class="comment"># get in folder</span></span><br><span class="line">ssh-keygen -t rsa -P <span class="string">''</span>                 <span class="comment"># generate id_rsa</span></span><br><span class="line">cat id_rsa.pub &gt;&gt; authorized_keys		<span class="comment"># vm01 now can ssh to itself</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<p><strong>Still on vm01</strong>, use ssh and scp to control vm02 ~ vm05.</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">scp ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub vm02:~/            <span class="comment"># copy id_rsa_pub to vm02</span></span><br><span class="line">ssh vm02 <span class="string">"cd ~;mkdir .ssh; cat ~/id_rsa.pub &gt;&gt; ~/.ssh/authorized_keys"</span>    <span class="comment"># add keys to vm02</span></span><br><span class="line">ssh vm02 <span class="string">"cd ~/.ssh; ssh-keygen -t rsa -P ''"</span>    <span class="comment"># vm02 generate key</span></span><br><span class="line">scp -r vm02:~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub vm01:~/id_rsa_vm02.pub           <span class="comment"># copy back to vm01</span></span><br><span class="line">cat ~/id_rsa_vm02.pub &gt;&gt; ~/.ssh/authorized_keys        <span class="comment"># add kyes to vm01</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<p>The above script on one hand generates ssh key for vm02, send it back to vm01, and then add it to vm01’s authroized key. On the other hand, it also adds vm01’s ssh key to vm02’s authorized key. By doing so, vm01 and vm02 can communicate with each other without password.</p>
<p>As the result, you should be able to log into another machine without password. For instance,<br><figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">ssh vm02  <span class="comment"># on vm01</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="built_in">exit</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<h2 id="Install-Java"><a href="#Install-Java" class="headerlink" title="Install Java"></a>Install Java</h2><p>First, uninstall open-jdk<br><figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">sudo apt-get update</span><br><span class="line">sudo apt-get remove java*</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<p>Then, download <a href="http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Java SE jdk</a>, unzip it, change its folder name to jdk by removing version number, and upload it to vm01 via WinSCP. By removing version number form the name, it makes upgrade easier. Usally a version.txt file can be added in the folder to track the version number.</p>
<p>Upload it to /home/hadoop/softwares/jdk via WinSCP. Then run the following</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="built_in">cd</span> ~/softwares/jdk</span><br><span class="line">sudo chmod a+x bin/*         <span class="comment"># change them to executable</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<p>Then add java to the path</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">sudo vim /etc/profile</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<p>Add the following to the end of /etc/profile<br><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">JAVA_HOME=/home/hadoop/softwares/jdk</span><br><span class="line">ZOOKEEPER_HOME=/home/hadoop/softwares/zookeeper</span><br><span class="line">HADOOP_HOME=/home/hadoop/softwares/hadoop</span><br><span class="line">SCALA_HOME=/home/hadoop/softwares/scala</span><br><span class="line">SPARK_HOME=/home/hadoop/softwares/spark</span><br><span class="line">HBASE_HOME=/home/hadoop/softwares/hbase</span><br><span class="line">CLASSPATH=.:$JAVA_HOME/lib/dt.jar:$JAVA_HOME/lib/tools.jar</span><br><span class="line">PATH=$JAVA_HOME/bin:$ZOOKEEPER_HOME/bin:$HADOOP_HOME/bin:$SCALA_HOME/bin:$SPARK_HOME/bin:$HBASE_HOME/bin:$PATH</span><br><span class="line">export JAVA_HOME CLASSPATH PATH ZOOKEEPER_HOME HADOOP_HOME SCALA_HOME SPARK_HOME HBASE_HOME</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<p>For the record, we don’t need SCALA_HOME or HBASE_HOME at this time, but just add it for the futures sake.</p>
<p>At last, source the profile setting into effect.<br><figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="built_in">source</span> /etc/profile</span><br><span class="line">java -version</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<p>Copy java to the rest four machines and modify their /etc/profile simiarly.<br><figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">scp -r /home/hadoop/softwares/jdk vm02:/home/hadoop/softwares/jdk</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<h2 id="Install-Zookeeper"><a href="#Install-Zookeeper" class="headerlink" title="Install Zookeeper"></a>Install Zookeeper</h2><p>Now it’s time to install <a href="http://zookeeper.apache.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">zookeeper</a>, the person who oversees all the animals in this zoo. Download, unzip, and upload it to vm01:/home/softwares/zookeeper via WinSCP.</p>
<p>Now change its config file</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="built_in">cd</span> /home/hadoop/softwares/zookeeper/</span><br><span class="line">chmod a+x bin/*				<span class="comment"># mark it executable</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="built_in">cd</span> conf</span><br><span class="line">cp zoo_sample.cfg zoo.cfg</span><br><span class="line">sudo vim zoo.cfg</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<p>and add the cluster info<br><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">dataDir=/home/hadoop/runtime/zookeeper/zkdata			# create this folder</span><br><span class="line">dataLogDir=/home/hadoop/runtime/zookeeper/zkdatalog		# create this folder</span><br><span class="line">clientPort=2181		# default zookeeper port</span><br><span class="line"># servers</span><br><span class="line">server.1=vm01:2888:3888</span><br><span class="line">server.2=vm02:2888:3888</span><br><span class="line">server.3=vm03:2888:3888</span><br><span class="line">server.4=vm04:2888:3888</span><br><span class="line">server.5=vm05:2888:3888</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<p>Distribute zookeeper to the rest four machines.<br><figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">scp -r /home/hadoop/softwares/zookeeper vm02:/home/hadoop/softwares/zookeeper</span><br><span class="line">ssh vm02 <span class="string">"mkdir -p /home/hadoop/runtime/zookeeper/zkdata"</span></span><br><span class="line">ssh vm02 <span class="string">"mkdir -p /home/hadoop/runtime/zookeeper/zkdatalog"</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<p>Next go to vm01, tell zookeeper its machine id,<br><figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="built_in">cd</span> ~/runtime/zookeeper/zkdata</span><br><span class="line"><span class="built_in">echo</span> <span class="string">"1"</span> &gt; myid</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<p><strong>Do this for the next four machines</strong>, echo “2” on vm02, “3” on vm03, and so on. By doing so, each machine has a file call myid, containing 1~5 respectively.</p>
<p>Finally we are ready to start zookeeper. Start it on every machine, one by one<br><figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="built_in">cd</span> /home/hadoop/softwares/zookeeper</span><br><span class="line">bin/zkServer.sh start     <span class="comment"># stop, status</span></span><br><span class="line">jps</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p>
<p>where QuorumPeerMain is the zookeeper process.</p>
<img src="/cloud-service-two/start_zookeeper.gif" title="start zookeeper">
<h2 id="Install-Hadoop"><a href="#Install-Hadoop" class="headerlink" title="Install Hadoop"></a>Install Hadoop</h2><p>Finally we are ready to install <a href="http://hadoop.apache.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">hadoop</a>. Download, unzip, and upload it to vm01:/home/softwares/hadoop via WinSCP</p>
<p>There are six cofiguration files to set. They all reside etc/hadoop folder.</p>
<p>(1)  core-site.xml</p>
<p>Add the following into configuration section, and create tmp folder on all five machines.</p>
